{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \DQ, top of your \DQ-J-T sequence — a safe, solid lead against the slam.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 6\H, and one loser is written in stone: West's lone \HA sits offside, and you cannot finesse against a singleton ace, so you will lose it. That means every other trick must come home. Count them: eight trump tricks, the \DA, the \CA, and the \SA make eleven. The twelfth is a spade — you hold \SA-Q facing dummy, missing the \SK. East opened 1\C while West could only preempt in diamonds, so the high cards, the \SK included, are marked with East.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \DQ, top of a sequence; win the \DA. You must lose the \HA, so drive it out and draw trumps. For the twelfth trick, lead a spade toward your \SA-Q and finesse: play the \SQ. East holds the \SK, so it is trapped behind your tenace and the queen wins. This is not a blind guess — East opened the bidding and West's weak jump denied values, placing the \SK squarely with East. Take the marked finesse and claim the slam.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The singleton \HA was a loser you could not avoid, so the slam rested on a single finesse for the \SK. Counting told you that you needed it; the auction told you it would work. East opened and West preempted weakly, so the king was marked, and finessing into the hand that bid brought home twelve. Even at the six level, you let the bidding answer the question. Well played.}
